# VERIFY — Slice <id> <title>

## Verdict
**verify_status:** `executed`  ·  one line: <why this verdict>
> A verdict of `verified` is permitted ONLY if: every acceptance criterion PASSes on its OWN surface,
> every load-bearing claim is Confirmed/Evidence-backed, all required gates are closed, and the
> verifier was a REAL distinct lens from the author. Otherwise the slice caps at `executed`.

### How to fill `impl_fingerprint` (semantic freshness, not timestamp)
Run `node <tools>/verify-fingerprint.mjs compute --changed` and paste its single-line JSON into the
`impl_fingerprint:` frontmatter value. It records the **normalized** fingerprint of the impl files this
VERIFY covers, so the gate can revalidate by **behavior**, not by mtime: a real behavior change makes the
current fingerprint diverge → this VERIFY goes stale → re-verify; non-functional edits (comments,
formatting, rebases, merge commits) keep the fingerprint → the VERIFY stays valid. **Omit the field** to
fall back to the legacy mtime (timestamp) check.
> Parser note: a trailing inline `# comment` on a frontmatter VALUE (e.g. `verify_status: verified # note`)
> is now **tolerated** by the fixed parser (it strips it), but is **still best avoided** — keep the
> `verify_status:` value line clean and put any legend on its own `#` line.

## Independence header  (Governance §3/§12 — proves author ≠ verifier)
- Verifier identity / invocation: <distinct agent id · session · timestamp — NOT the build session>
- Author identity (code under test): <id/session>
- [ ] I assert: the verifier did **not** author the production code under test.
- [ ] Independence was **real** (a true second invocation, not the same context restyled). If not → mark non-independent; status caps at `executed`.

## Execution evidence  (Governance §1 — direct runtime output, never a description of what *would* happen)
| # | Command | Exit | Output (verbatim / log path) |
|---|---------|------|------------------------------|
| 1 | `<cmd>` | 0 | `<actual stdout/stderr>` |
> A row with no command + real output is not evidence. Prose is not evidence.
> **Machine-guard line (shared resources):** when the verification touches a shared store/queue/port, state the
> guard here — run-unique tokens in every fixture/assertion + the preamble proving the resource is YOURS
> (e.g. listening PID checked; DB name asserted `*_test`). Earned: the same shared-resource race recurred three
> times before run-unique tokens fixed it; a stale server on the expected port once nearly poisoned a verdict.

## Acceptance criteria  (copied verbatim from the slice — each PASS/FAIL + its evidence pointer)
| # | Criterion | Surface exercised | Evidence (→ cmd #) | PASS/FAIL |
|---|-----------|-------------------|--------------------|-----------|
| 1 | <…> | <HTTP→running app / imports src / fresh-DB migration> | #n | PASS/FAIL |
> A criterion whose evidence does NOT touch its own surface is FAIL — regardless of a green check.
> (Slice-1.0 lesson: raw SQL does not verify an API criterion; DDL-only does not verify app behavior.)

## Surface statement  (anti-Slice-1.0)
- The slice's real surface: <app / API / migration>. Driven by: <how the tests reach it>.
- [ ] No criterion was "verified" via a surface that bypasses the slice (e.g. raw SQL for an app criterion; reading code instead of running it).

